g.text: NuGet Packages can change at a different rate
- Good news: You can update to the dependency
- Good news: Since you are bound to a specific version,
no future changes will impact your app.
- Bad news: You can fall behind.
- Bad news: You don't get the future changes until you
decide to rebuild your application to use the newer
Any external dependency that is "baked" into your application
(e.g. Nuget) is by design stable and a snapshot of that dependency
This means if your team is, for example, sharing code through NuGet packages
two different services your team owns may be using different versions of the library.
You are "early bound" (at build time) to that version.
Your Dependency is on an address (endpoint)
Good News: The External Service can change independently
from your service. No need to redeploy if the services
implementation changes (bug fixes, new features, etc.)
Bad News: A lot of trust is needed. Breaking changes
in the external service will break your app.
Bad News: There is a network there. More fragility.
One Application / Many "Libraries" that depend on one another.
A change in part of the application triggers a redeploy of the entire application.
As a matter of fact it is almost ALL good news.
- A small change in one part of the system can't be elevated without elevating the entire system.
- This also means that your team must know EVERYTHING and own EVERYTHING.
- In focused businesses / domains this is possible (e.g. StackOverflow)
- The "server" that runs your application has to be large enough to accomodate the peak load of the slowest portion of your application.
Note: Class Libraries in a Visual Studio Solution were meant to be independt units of deployment but rarely are they used that way.
They are primarily used to create "guardrails" for people.
Another Note: This is almost completely a fiction. An app that doesn't rely on any "Attached Resource" rarely is useful. There are always dependencies.
e.g. Databases, Web Servers, User Interface, etc.
Create an "App" - Twelve Factor App language. A repository that is deployed together*.
Changes in Project 1 do not trigger a redeploy of Project Two
Changes in Project 2 do not trigger a redeploy of Project One
Changes in Library DOES trigger a redeploy of Project One and Two
- This takes a bit of pipeline wizardry, but not too bad.
